{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489269"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:10:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:10:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"620"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/620"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.03,0.06,0.15,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"620"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41881"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/620"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"620"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26853"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3339"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2834"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3462"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41881"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to his General Practice with a three-day history of a sore throat and fever. His symptoms have deteriorated despite conservative management including three days of paracetamol, oral fluids and bed rest. He does not have any shortness of breath, chest pain, nausea, or vomiting. He has a medical history of schizophrenia, hyperthyroidism, osteoarthritis and asthma. His current medications include perindopril, carbimazole, salbutamol, clozapine and ibuprofen. On examination, he looks flushed. His pulse is 100/min, blood pressure 130/70mmHg and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. No other abnormalities are detected on examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important laboratory investigation to order?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Full blood count","Sputum culture","Thyroid function tests","Throat swab","Clozapine level"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe concern is that the patient might have drug-induced agranulocytosis. He is taking two agents (clozapine and carbimazole) that could cause this (rare) side-effect. A \u003Cstrong\u003Efull blood count\u003C/strong\u003E can be done to check for drug-induced agranulocytosis. If he does have agranulocytosis, the patient is at risk of developing a life-threatening infection. The drugs will need to be ceased immediately and he almost certainly will require prompt hospitalisation for treatment of febrile neutropenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough a \u003Cstrong\u003Esputum culture\u003C/strong\u003E or a \u003Cstrong\u003Ethroat swab\u003C/strong\u003E might reveal the microbial agent that is the cause of this patient\u0027s symptoms and may change management, it is less crucial than a full blood count. Furthermore, if this patient does not have agranulocytosis, his sore throat and fever can likely be treated conservatively without a need for sputum culture or throat swab.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid function tests\u003C/strong\u003E are unlikely to be useful in directing management either. His symptoms do not suggest a clinical picture of hyperthyroidism or hypothyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimilarly, a \u003Cstrong\u003Eclozapine level\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to change management; it is used to titrate and monitor response to symptoms in the commencement of clozapine therapy. This patient is not showing any signs of clozapine toxicity such as seizures and cardiac arrhythmias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Patients on clozapine and/or carbimazole who present with fever should always undergo a full blood count to rule out drug-induced agranulocytosis."],"references":["Curtis BR. Drug-induced immune neutropenia/agranulocytosis. Immunohematology. 2014;30(2):95-101. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25247619/","Ellis M. Febrile neutropenia. Ann N Y Acad Sci. 2008;1138:329-50. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18837909/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26853"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"620"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26853"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-25T21:40:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-25T21:40:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"620"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41881"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"descrip